From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: VIKINGYFY <vikingyfy@immortalwrt.org>
Date: Sat, 2 May 2026 00:00:00 +0800
Subject: [PATCH] wifi: cfg80211: relax max bandwidth check in reg rule
 validation

The is_valid_reg_rule() function rejects regulatory rules where
max_bandwidth_khz exceeds the frequency range. However, some
ath11k firmware (notably for the CN regulatory domain) reports
rules where the maximum bandwidth is larger than the frequency
range width, causing the entire regulatory domain to be rejected
and spamming the kernel log with WARNING backtraces.

The bandwidth constraint is already enforced by
reg_get_max_bandwidth_from_range() which clamps the result to
the actual range width. The validation here is redundant and
overly strict, causing regressions from kernel 6.12 where this
check did not exist.

Remove the redundant bandwidth check and the redundant
end_freq/start_freq check (which is already verified above),
returning to the 6.12 behavior.

Signed-off-by: VIKINGYFY <vikingyfy@immortalwrt.org>
---
 net/wireless/reg.c | 7 -------
 1 file changed, 7 deletions(-)

--- a/net/wireless/reg.c
+++ b/net/wireless/reg.c
@@ -1235,7 +1235,6 @@ unsigned int reg_get_max_bandwidth(cons
 static bool is_valid_reg_rule(const struct ieee80211_reg_rule *rule)
 {
 	const struct ieee80211_freq_range *freq_range = &rule->freq_range;
-	u32 freq_diff;
 
 	if (freq_range->start_freq_khz <= 0 || freq_range->end_freq_khz <= 0)
 		return false;
@@ -1243,12 +1242,6 @@ static bool is_valid_reg_rule(const str
 	if (freq_range->start_freq_khz > freq_range->end_freq_khz)
 		return false;
 
-	freq_diff = freq_range->end_freq_khz - freq_range->start_freq_khz;
-
-	if (freq_range->end_freq_khz <= freq_range->start_freq_khz ||
-	    freq_range->max_bandwidth_khz > freq_diff)
-		return false;
-
 	return true;
 }
 
